data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. Here's the explanation:

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` mean that `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (which operates on spans) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` so the compiler binds to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

All three force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which expression trees can represent.
